Azure Management Groups provide a way to organize multiple subscriptions under a single hierarchy. They allow centralized management of access, policies, and compliance.

For example, a company can create a management group for all production subscriptions and apply security policies at the group level.

A real-life use case is a large enterprise with hundreds of subscriptions. Instead of managing each subscription individually, administrators can manage them collectively using management groups.

Another example is enforcing policies such as restricting resource locations or requiring specific security configurations across all subscriptions.

Management groups simplify governance and ensure consistency across large-scale Azure environments.
